I now have enough information to give a complete, precise answer. The knowledge graph has surfaced three directly relevant anti-patterns (AP-064, EAP-077, EAP-080) and their exact prescribed fix. Let me synthesize everything into the diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The bug is a well-documented failure mode that has hit this codebase twice before — on the login page (FB-129 / ENG-139) and again as a regression (ENG-141). The symptom is always identical: the top of display-scale serif glyphs is clipped, and raising `padding-top` on the `<input>` does nothing.

### What's actually happening (the rendering model)

A native `<input type="text">` is a **replaced element**. The browser — not the CSS box model — controls how its text content is positioned inside the field's client rect. The UA stylesheet for `<input>` imposes its own internal text-inset regime that is **separate from CSS padding**. At body-copy sizes (12–18 px) the UA's internal inset is generous enough that even an ascender-heavy font has clearance. At display scale — IBM Plex Serif at `heading-case-study-intro` fluid size (~36–60 px) — the situation inverts:

1. **Line-height vs cap-height mismatch.** `heading-case-study-intro` uses `line-height: 1.25` (snug). At 60 px that is a 75 px line box. IBM Plex Serif's cap-height ratio is ~0.71 and its ascender ratio is ~0.92 — meaning the ascender extends to ~55 px above the baseline. The 75 px line box nominally fits, but …

2. **The UA text-inset crushes the top half.** The browser allocates the glyph's vertical position inside the input field based on its own internal metrics (typically `font-size * 0.5` baseline offset from the center of the field). At large sizes this means the baseline is set near the vertical centre of the field rectangle, and the ascending portion of the glyph rides up into — and past — the top edge of the input's content box, where it is clipped by the input's native overflow boundary.

3. **`padding-top` on the `<input>` shifts the content box downward without moving the glyph.** Because the text cursor/caret and glyph are positioned by the replaced-element renderer, not the CSS box model, more `padding-top` just makes the field taller; the glyph stays glued to its UA-computed vertical position relative to the field rectangle. This is exactly the "padding trap" documented in **EAP-077**.

4. **`overflow: hidden` is the secondary offender.** If there is an `overflow: hidden` on any ancestor (a containing block, a scroll region, or even the input's own wrapper), it silently activates glyph clipping for ascenders/descenders that exceed the element's paint boundary. **EAP-080** codifies this.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-064 — Native `<input>` text rendering for display-scale serif fonts.**  
**EAP-077 — Assuming CSS can fix `<input>` native text clipping for oversized serif fonts.**  
**EAP-080 — Adding `overflow: hidden` to display-scale serif text without glyph padding.**

The anti-patterns prescribe the same canonical fix that was successfully applied for FB-129 on the login page: **replace the `<input>` with a `<div contentEditable>` (or `<textarea>` made transparent with custom rendering) and apply the typography mixin to the element directly.** A `contentEditable` div is an ordinary block-level element; its text is painted by the layout engine, not the replaced-element renderer, so CSS padding is fully honoured, ascenders never clip, and `line-height` behaves normally.

---

## Fix

The case study editor's display-scale title field lives in two files:

```
src/components/inline-edit/DisplayTitleInput.tsx       ← React component
src/components/inline-edit/inline-edit.module.scss     ← styles
```

*(If the component is named differently in your tree, grep for the selector that applies `heading-case-study-intro` or `font-family: var(--font-ibm-plex-serif)` inside an `<input>`.)*

### Step 1 — Replace `<input>` with `contentEditable`

**Before (`DisplayTitleInput.tsx`):**
```tsx
// ❌ native <input> — UA renderer clips display-scale glyphs
<input
  type="text"
  value={value}
  onChange={e => onChange(e.target.value)}
  className={styles.titleInput}
  placeholder={placeholder}
/>
```

**After:**
```tsx
// ✅ contentEditable div — layout engine paints glyphs; CSS padding is honoured
import { useRef, useEffect } from 'react'

export function DisplayTitleInput({ value, onChange, placeholder }: Props) {
  const ref = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null)

  // Sync external value → DOM (without clobbering cursor position)
  useEffect(() => {
    if (ref.current && ref.current.textContent !== value) {
      ref.current.textContent = value ?? ''
    }
  }, [value])

  return (
    <div
      ref={ref}
      role="textbox"
      aria-multiline="false"
      aria-label={placeholder}
      contentEditable
      suppressContentEditableWarning
      data-placeholder={placeholder}        // styled via CSS attr()
      className={styles.titleInput}
      onInput={e => onChange((e.target as HTMLDivElement).textContent ?? '')}
      onKeyDown={e => {
        if (e.key === 'Enter') {
          // Prevent <br> insertion — this is a single-line display title
          e.preventDefault()
        }
      }}
    />
  )
}
```

**Why `textContent` sync in `useEffect` instead of `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`:**  
`dangerouslySetInnerHTML` on a `contentEditable` causes React to nuke and re-create the DOM node on every keystroke, resetting cursor position to 0. The `useEffect` guard only writes when the external value diverges from the DOM, so it only fires when a *programmatic* change (CMS save round-trip) needs to update the field — not on user typing.

---

### Step 2 — Update the SCSS module

**`src/components/inline-edit/inline-edit.module.scss`**

```scss
// ❌ Before — padding on <input> moved the box but not the glyphs
.titleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;
  width: 100%;
  padding: $portfolio-spacer-1x $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;   // had no effect on clipping
  border: none;
  background: transparent;
  outline: none;

  &:focus {
    outline: none;
  }
}
```

```scss
// ✅ After — padding on contentEditable is honoured by the layout engine
.titleInput {
  @include heading-case-study-intro;
  width: 100%;
  display: block;

  // Glyph-safe vertical inset:
  // The ascender of IBM Plex Serif at display scale protrudes ~0.2em above
  // the cap-height. padding-block adds real layout space — unlike on <input>,
  // this actually pushes the glyph away from the container edge.
  padding-block: 0.25em;          // ← safe inset for ascender + descender
  padding-inline: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;

  border: none;
  background: transparent;
  outline: none;
  cursor: text;
  white-space: pre-wrap;          // preserve intentional spacing
  word-break: break-word;
  overflow-wrap: break-word;

  // Placeholder via attr() — avoids a second DOM element
  &:empty::before {
    content: attr(data-placeholder);
    color: var(--portfolio-color-text-placeholder, #9ca3af);
    pointer-events: none;
  }

  // Engaged state — consistent with AP-054 canonical (1px base + 1px box-shadow ring)
  &:focus {
    outline: none;
    box-shadow: 0 0 0 1px var(--portfolio-color-border-focus);
  }

  // ⚠ Never add overflow: hidden here or on any ancestor wrapping display-scale
  // serif text. See EAP-080.
}
```

**Critical rule: `overflow: hidden` must not appear on this element or any wrapping ancestor.** Check the containing block chain in DevTools. Common offenders are `.adminFieldWrapper`, `.editorScrollRegion`, or any element with `overflow-y: auto` that also constrains height.

---

### Step 3 — Check the ancestor overflow chain

```
src/app/(admin)/collections/work/[slug]/page.tsx        ← the editor page
src/components/inline-edit/InlineEditWrapper.tsx        ← field container
```

In DevTools, select the title input and walk up the tree. Flag any element that has:
- `overflow: hidden`
- `overflow-y: auto` **with a fixed height** (auto on fixed height creates a clipping rectangle)

For each offender, change to:
```scss
overflow: visible;           // if the clip was accidental
// — or —
overflow-y: auto;            // remove the fixed height; use min-height instead
min-height: <value>;
```

---

## What's Structurally Different About Display-Scale Fonts in Inputs

Here is the complete mental model, so you can predict this problem anywhere in the design system:

### The two rendering paths

| Element | Who positions the text | CSS `padding` effect |
|---|---|---|
| `<div>`, `<p>`, `<span>`, `<textarea>` (stylised) | **Layout engine** (Blink/WebKit block formatting context) | Fully honoured — padding adds real layout space around the glyph |
| `<input type="text">` | **Replaced-element renderer** (browser UA internal) | Moves the *box* but not the *glyph position inside the box* |

### Why it only surfaces at display scale

At 14–18 px (body copy), IBM Plex Serif's ascenders are ~16 px tall. The UA renderer's internal vertical inset for `<input>` — roughly `0.5 × font-size` of clearance above and below the baseline cluster — comfortably contains them.

At 36–60 px (display scale), ascenders reach ~55 px above the baseline. The UA's internal inset is now only ~18–30 px of clearance. The ascender overflows the inset and hits the `<input>`'s native clip boundary. You'd need to reduce `font-size` until the ascender fits inside the UA inset — which is the wrong fix.

### Why `padding-top` feels like it should work but doesn't

`padding-top` on `<input>` adds to the element's *outer box height*, shifting the field's bottom edge downward. The UA renderer sees a taller field and recomputes the baseline position — still roughly vertical-centre of the field rectangle. The glyph moves with the new centre, never gaining clearance at the top. You can keep adding padding forever; the clip chases the glyph upward at the same rate.

### The `line-height: 1` trap

Some teams try `line-height: 1` to shrink the line box and "lower" the glyphs. This has the opposite of the intended effect: a collapsed line box gives the UA renderer even *less* vertical headroom, making the clip more severe, not less. The `heading-case-study-intro` mixin uses `line-height: 1.25` which is already as tight as is safe.

### The `overflow: hidden` multiplier

If *any* ancestor has `overflow: hidden`, the browser's normal behaviour of painting glyph ink outside the element's layout rect (which is how ascenders and descenders are rendered without clip even without extra padding) is suppressed. This is a secondary clip source that operates independently of the `<input>` UA renderer problem — and it affects `contentEditable` and `<textarea>` too, not just `<input>`. The fix there is always `overflow: visible` on the ancestor, or glyph-safe `padding-block` that keeps the ink inside the rect. (EAP-080.)

### The canonical solution rule

> Any display-scale serif text (`heading-case-study-intro`, `quote-lg`, or any mixin ≥ `$portfolio-type-4xl` with `font-family: $portfolio-font-serif`) that is **editable** must be implemented as `contentEditable`, never as `<input>`. Apply `padding-block: 0.25em` as the minimum glyph-safe inset. Never wrap in `overflow: hidden`.

This is now the second time this exact bug has been fixed in this codebase. After applying the fix, add a comment in `DisplayTitleInput.tsx` citing **AP-064** and **EAP-077** so the next engineer understands why the element is a div and not an input.
